BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 30 KYODO -- The Ministry of Finance 
[MOF] plans to allow a portion of the revenues collected from 
the consumption tax to be handled by local governments, ministry 
sources said Monday [30 May]. 
  The ministry will soon offer a compromise proposal to the 
Home Affairs Ministry, which, along with local governments, has 
urged the introduction of a local consumption tax. 
  Currently, the state government collects all consumption tax 
revenues and distributes 20 percent of revenues to autonomies. 
  Under the Finance Ministry proposal, the same proportion of 
income from the consumption tax will be collected by 
municipalities and then pooled and distributed according to 
population and consumption levels. 
  Introduction of a local consumption tax is one of the 
focuses 
in the planned tax system overhaul the government plans to work 
out by late June. 
  The Finance Ministry initially opposed the idea but has 
conceded in the face of mounting calls for the need to boost the 
financial base of local governments. 
  Its proposal is slightly different from that of the Home 
Affairs Ministry, which requested that Japan's 47 prefectures 
collect the tax and the money gathered be distributed in 
accordance with the number of workers in each prefecture. 
  If the Finance Ministry's plan is accepted, the share of 
revenues for such major cities as Tokyo and Osaka will be much 
smaller than the original plan because many people who work in 
the major cities live outside city limits. 

</TEXT>

