  [Text] Fukui, March 30 KYODO -- Activists of the 
international environmental organization Greenpeace arrived 
Wednesday [30 March] aboard the patrol boat MV Greenpeace in 
Tsuruga, Fukui Prefecture, to protest the start-up of Japan's 
prototype fast breeder reactor Monju there. 
  During the 10-day port call at Tsuruga, Captain Arne 
Sorensen 
and 18 Greenpeace activists will inform local residents of the 
dangers Monju poses for the environment in videos and a photo 
exhibition on the boat, spokeswoman Etsuko Ikeda said. 
  The fast breeder operated by the governmental Power Reactor 
and Nuclear Fuel Development Corp. will soon reach what is 
called "criticality," the stage when a nuclear chain reaction is 
self-sustaining. Ikeda said Greenpeace estimates Monju will 
reach criticality on April 8. 
  The reactor, which uses a mixture of highly toxic plutonium 
and enriched uranium as fuel, will then produce 280,000 
kilowatts of electricity. 
  In a recent report, Greenpeace warned that Monju "could 
explode like an atomic bomb, killing thousands and contaminating 
most population centers in Japan and neighboring countries." 
  Greenpeace also alleged that the Japanese Government is 
withholding important data on the safety risk posed by Monju. 
Noting that the original safety assessment for the fast breeder 
was undertaken over 10 years ago, Greenpeace called for a new 
safety review and a full environmental impact statement. 
  On its previous mission last October, the MV Greenpeace 
monitored nuclear waste dumped into the Sea of Japan by Russia 
and the former Soviet Union. 

</TEXT>

